### Describe the bug

While working on possible additional Blazor binding coverage, I noticed an unexpected behavior that I'd like to ask about. It kind'a looks like a bug, but it's probably designed behavior.

While asking about the unexpected behavior here, I'd like to toss in two additional, related side questions at the end, also for potential docs coverage related to this question.

# Main question on unexpected framework behavior

I've reviewed open binding work and answered questions, but I don't see my question mentioned:

* [Add support for binding decimal, double, float data type with configurable formatting (dotnet/aspnetcore #5523)](https://github.com/dotnet/aspnetcore/issues/5523)
* [two way binding does not yet handle color picker in blazor (dotnet/aspnetcore #10376)](https://github.com/dotnet/aspnetcore/issues/10376)

We currently cover [property-based custom binding](https://docs.microsoft.com/aspnet/core/blazor/components/data-binding#custom-binding-formats), and the example uses a `decimal`. The strange behavior occurs using property-based binding with a color picker (`<input type="color" @bind="PickerColor" />` where `PickerColor` is a `string`).

The following example doesn't set the color picker `value` correctly (to forest green) when the component is first rendered, then it **_works as expected_** when a color is picked by the user after the component is loaded.

```razor
@using System.Drawing 

<p>
    <input type="color" @bind="PickerColor" />
</p>

<p>
    color: @color
</p>

@code {
    private Color color = Color.ForestGreen;

    private string PickerColor
    {
        get => ColorTranslator.ToHtml(color);
        set
        {
            color = ColorTranslator.FromHtml(value);
        }
    }
}
```

Initial load:

<img width="501" alt="a-failing-load" src="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1622880/159280461-96075102-3f19-4970-b216-b41c07331792.png">

After picking red:

<img width="501" alt="a-failing-picked" src="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1622880/159280478-f8d0ab2b-dd39-42b5-be98-b7ab2e93ba17.png">

**_Setting the `PickerColor` with a formatted string (that drops the alpha) does work:_**

```csharp
get => string.Format("#{0:X6}", color.ToArgb() & 0x00FFFFFF);
```

Initial load with the preceding `get`:

<img width="501" alt="a-working-load" src="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1622880/159280523-57e5cd0e-d750-483e-af5d-4900f59a94c4.png">

‚ùì Why does the `ToHtml` initially fail, then work fine thereafter via user color picks? I expected that if `ToHtml` is going to fail that it would fail for both the initial render **_and_** on change events.

I'm not necessarily suggesting that we'll document this behavior, but we might depending on the answer.

# Side questions while I'm here

An entirely different approach is to use a `CreateBinder`, which works fine (initial value and user picks):

```razor
@using System.Drawing 

<p>
    <input type="color"
            value="@string.Format("#{0:X6}", color.ToArgb() & 0x00FFFFFF)"
            @onchange="EventCallback.Factory.CreateBinder<Color>(
                this, __value => color = __value, color)" />
</p>

<p>
    color: @color
</p>

@code {
    private Color color = Color.ForestGreen;
}
```

... and works well with color logic as ...

```razor
@using System.Drawing 

<p>
    <input type="color"
            value="@string.Format("#{0:X6}", color.ToArgb() & 0x00FFFFFF)"
            @onchange="EventCallback.Factory.CreateBinder<Color>(
                this,
                __value => color = ColorLogic(__value),
                color)" />
</p>

<p>
    color: @color
</p>

@code {
    private Color color = Color.ForestGreen;

    private Color ColorLogic(Color c)
    {
        if (c == Color.Red)
        {
            return Color.Blue;
        }

        return c;
    }
}
```

‚ùì **_Side question 1:_** The PU never called for docs on the use of `CreateBinder` for any purpose. This is a case where it seems like a fair (but perhaps advanced) approach. Should we cover it? If so, can you define some basic guidance on its use:

* What use cases is it best suited for? Where should it be avoided?
* Should we dissuade its use slightly by describing it as an "advanced" scenario?
* Any perf or security concerns?

**_BTW_**: A community dev did say that they found `CreateBinder` useful in their app that works with `DataTable`/`DataRow` at https://github.com/dotnet/AspNetCore.Docs/issues/16370. In fact, that's what generated the whole docs discussion in the first place. In spite of working for them, the dev was looking for a less gritty approach than `CreateBinder`, leading to my 2nd question üëá, which might be better for their use case (*not sure*, just speculating).

‚ùì **_Side question 2:_** The PU also never requested `TypeConverter` coverage for any purpose.

https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.componentmodel.typeconverter

I haven't worked with them (*yet* ... I'd like to at least learn more). I see it in framework tests. For example, there's a `[TypeConverter(typeof(PersonConverter))]` test at ...

https://github.com/dotnet/aspnetcore/blob/main/src/Components/Components/test/BindConverterTest.cs#L380-L429

Should we cover `TypeConverter`? If so ...

* What use cases is it best suited for? Where should it be avoided?
* Should we dissuade its use slightly by describing it as an "advanced" scenario?
* Any perf or security concerns?

